[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In mathematics and physics (more specifically thermodynamics), the **heat equation** is a parabolic partial differential equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The theory of the heat equation was first developed by Joseph Fourier in 1822 for the purpose of modeling how a quantity such as heat diffuses through a given region.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Since then, the heat equation and its variants have been found to be fundamental in many parts of both pure and applied mathematics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] where $(x_{1},x_{2},\cdots ,x_{n},t)$ denotes a general point of the domain.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] It is typical to refer to t as time and $(x_{1},x_{2},\cdots ,x_{n})$ as spatial variables, even in abstract contexts where these phrases fail to have their intuitive meaning.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The collection of spatial variables is often referred to simply as x.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] For any given value of t, the right-hand side of the equation is the Laplacian of the function $u(\cdot ,t):U\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In physics and engineering contexts, especially in the context of diffusion through a medium, it is more common to fix a Cartesian coordinate system and then to consider the specific case of a function $u(x,y,z,t)$ of three spatial variables $(x,y,z)$ and time variable t .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] in which $\alpha$ is a positive coefficient called the thermal diffusivity of the medium.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In addition to other physical phenomena, this equation describes the flow of heat in a homogeneous and isotropic medium, with $u(x,y,z,t)$ being the temperature at the point $(x,y,z)$ and time t .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] If the medium is not homogeneous and isotropic, then $\alpha$ would not be a fixed coefficient, and would instead depend on $(x,y,z)$ ; the equation would also have a slightly different form.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In some physics and engineering literature, it is common to use $\Delta$ to denote the Laplacian, rather than $\nabla ^{2}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] But the "nabla-squared" $(\nabla ^{2})$ notation is more modern and recommended, while $\Delta$ may denote a simple change in some cases.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Note also that the ability to use either $\Delta$ or $\nabla ^{2}$ to denote the Laplacian, without explicit reference to the spatial variables, is a reflection of the fact that the Laplacian is independent of the choice of coordinate system.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In mathematical terms, one would say that the Laplacian is translationally and rotationally invariant.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In fact, it is (loosely speaking) the simplest differential operator which has these symmetries.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This can be taken as a significant (and purely mathematical) justification of the use of the Laplacian and of the heat equation in modeling any physical phenomena which are homogeneous and isotropic, of which heat diffusion is a principal example.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The diffusivity constant $\alpha$ is often not present in mathematical studies of the heat equation, while its value can be very important in engineering.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This is not a major difference, for the following reason.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Thus, there is a straightforward way of translating between solutions of the heat equation with a general value of $\alpha$ and solutions of the heat equation with $\alpha =1$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] As such, for the sake of mathematical analysis, it is often sufficient to only consider the case $\alpha =1$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Since $\alpha >0$ there is another option to define a v satisfying ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial }{\partial t}}v=\Delta v}$ as in (**⁎**) above by setting $v(t,x)=u\left(t,\alpha ^{\frac {1}{2}}x\right)$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Note that the two possible means of defining the new function v discussed here amount, in physical terms, to changing the unit of measure of time or the unit of measure of length.
