[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The inhomogeneous heat equation models thermal problems in which a heat source modeled by f is switched on.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] For example, it can be used to model the temperature throughout a room with a heater switched on.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] If $S\subset U$ is the region of the room where the heater is and the heater is constantly generating q units of heat per unit of volume, then f would be given by $f(x,t)=q1_{S}(x)$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Flowing *u* via. the heat equation causes it to become closer and closer as time increases to a steady-state solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] For very large time, *u* is closely approximated by a steady-state solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] A steady state solution of the heat equation is equivalently a solution of Laplace's equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This is equivalently a solution of Poisson's equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In the steady-state case, a nonzero spatial thermal gradient $\nabla u$ may (or may not) be present, but if it is, it does not change in time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The other (trivial) solution is for all spatial temperature gradients to disappear as well, in which case the temperature become uniform in space, as well.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The steady-state equations are simpler and can help to understand better the physics of the materials without focusing on the dynamics of heat transport.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] It is widely used for simple engineering problems assuming there is equilibrium of the temperature fields and heat transport, with time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Informally, the Laplacian operator $\nabla ^{2}$ gives the difference between the average value of a function in the neighborhood of a point, and its value at that point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Thus, if u is the temperature, $\nabla ^{2}u$ conveys if (and by how much) the material surrounding each point is hotter or colder, on the average, than the material at that point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] By the second law of thermodynamics, heat will flow from hotter bodies to adjacent colder bodies, in proportion to the difference of temperature and of the thermal conductivity of the material between them.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] When heat flows into (respectively, out of) a material, its temperature increases (respectively, decreases), in proportion to the amount of heat divided by the amount (mass) of material, with a proportionality factor called the specific heat capacity of the material.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] By the combination of these observations, the heat equation says the rate ${\dot {u}}$ at which the material at a point will heat up (or cool down) is proportional to how much hotter (or cooler) the surrounding material is.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The coefficient α in the equation takes into account the thermal conductivity, specific heat, and density of the material.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The first half of the above physical thinking can be put into a mathematical form.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] in which $\omega _{n-1}$ denotes the surface area of the unit ball in n -dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This formalizes the above statement that the value of $\nabla ^{2}u$ at a point x measures the difference between the value of $u(x)$ and the value of u at points nearby to x , in the sense that the latter is encoded by the values of $u_{(x)}(r)$ for small positive values of r .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Following this observation, one may interpret the heat equation as imposing an *infinitesimal averaging* of a function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Given a solution of the heat equation, the value of $u(x,t+\tau )$ for a small positive value of $\tau$ may be approximated as ${\frac {1}{2n}}$ times the average value of the function $u(\cdot ,t)$ over a sphere of very small radius centered at x .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The heat equation implies that peaks (local maxima) of u will be gradually eroded down, while depressions (local minima) will be filled in.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The value at some point will remain stable only as long as it is equal to the average value in its immediate surroundings.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In particular, if the values in a neighborhood are very close to a linear function $Ax+By+Cz+D$ , then the value at the center of that neighborhood will not be changing at that time (that is, the derivative ${\dot {u}}$ will be zero).
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] A more subtle consequence is the maximum principle, that says that the maximum value of u in any region R of the medium will not exceed the maximum value that previously occurred in R , unless it is on the boundary of R .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] That is, the maximum temperature in a region R can increase only if heat comes in from outside R .
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This is a property of parabolic partial differential equations and is not difficult to prove mathematically (see below).
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Another interesting property is that even if u initially has a sharp jump (discontinuity) of value across some surface inside the medium, the jump is immediately smoothed out by a momentary, infinitesimally short but infinitely large rate of flow of heat through that surface.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] If a certain amount of heat is suddenly applied to a point in the medium, it will spread out in all directions in the form of a diffusion wave.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Unlike the elastic and electromagnetic waves, the speed of a diffusion wave drops with time: as it spreads over a larger region, the temperature gradient decreases, and therefore the heat flow decreases too.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] For heat flow, the heat equation follows from the physical laws of conduction of heat and conservation of energy (Cannon 1984).
