[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] As the prototypical parabolic partial differential equation, the heat equation is among the most widely studied topics in pure mathematics, and its analysis is regarded as fundamental to the broader field of partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The heat equation can also be considered on Riemannian manifolds, leading to many geometric applications.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Following work of Subbaramiah Minakshisundaram and Åke Pleijel, the heat equation is closely related with spectral geometry.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] A seminal nonlinear variant of the heat equation was introduced to differential geometry by James Eells and Joseph Sampson in 1964, inspiring the introduction of the Ricci flow by Richard Hamilton in 1982 and culminating in the proof of the Poincaré conjecture by Grigori Perelman in 2003.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Certain solutions of the heat equation known as heat kernels provide subtle information about the region on which they are defined, as exemplified through their application to the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The heat equation, along with variants thereof, is also important in many fields of science and applied mathematics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In probability theory, the heat equation is connected with the study of random walks and Brownian motion via the Fokker–Planck equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The Black–Scholes equation of financial mathematics is a small variant of the heat equation, and the Schrödinger equation of quantum mechanics can be regarded as a heat equation in imaginary time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] In image analysis, the heat equation is sometimes used to resolve pixelation and to identify edges.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Following Robert Richtmyer and John von Neumann's introduction of artificial viscosity methods, solutions of heat equations have been useful in the mathematical formulation of hydrodynamical shocks.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Solutions of the heat equation have also been given much attention in the numerical analysis literature, beginning in the 1950s with work of Jim Douglas, D.W.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Both *c* and *P* are functions of position and time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] *D* is the diffusion coefficient that controls the speed of the diffusive process, and is typically expressed in meters squared over second.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] If the diffusion coefficient *D* is not constant, but depends on the concentration *c* (or *P* in the second case), then one gets the nonlinear diffusion equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] where B is the Wiener process (standard Brownian motion).
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] where $\delta$ is the Dirac delta function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] where *i* is the imaginary unit, *ħ* is the reduced Planck constant, and *ψ* is the wave function of the particle.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Remark: this analogy between quantum mechanics and diffusion is a purely formal one.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Physically, the evolution of the wave function satisfying the Schrödinger equation might have an origin other than diffusion.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] A direct practical application of the heat equation, in conjunction with Fourier theory, in spherical coordinates, is the prediction of thermal transfer profiles and the measurement of the thermal diffusivity in polymers (Unsworth and Duarte).
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This dual theoretical-experimental method is applicable to rubber, various other polymeric materials of practical interest, and microfluids.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] where *T*0 is the initial temperature of the sphere and TS the temperature at the surface of the sphere, of radius L.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This equation has also found applications in protein energy transfer and thermal modeling in biophysics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The heat equation arises in a number of phenomena and is often used in financial mathematics in the modeling of options.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The Black–Scholes option pricing model's differential equation can be transformed into the heat equation allowing relatively easy solutions from a familiar body of mathematics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Many of the extensions to the simple option models do not have closed form solutions and thus must be solved numerically to obtain a modeled option price.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The equation describing pressure diffusion in a porous medium is identical in form with the heat equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] Diffusion problems dealing with Dirichlet, Neumann and Robin boundary conditions have closed form analytic solutions (Thambynayagam 2011).
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The heat equation is also widely used in image analysis (Perona & Malik 1990) and in machine learning as the driving theory behind scale-space or graph Laplacian methods.
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] The heat equation can be efficiently solved numerically using the implicit Crank–Nicolson method of (Crank & Nicolson 1947).
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] This method can be extended to many of the models with no closed form solution, see for instance (Wilmott, Howison & Dewynne 1995).
[src:partial-differential-equations/heat-equation] An abstract form of heat equation on manifolds provides a major approach to the Atiyah–Singer index theorem, and has led to much further work on heat equations in Riemannian geometry.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In mathematics and physics, **Laplace's equation** is a second-order partial differential equation named after Pierre-Simon Laplace, who first studied its properties in 1786.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Laplace operator therefore maps a scalar function to another scalar function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This is called Poisson's equation, a generalization of Laplace's equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Laplace's equation and Poisson's equation are the simplest examples of elliptic partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Laplace's equation is also a special case of the Helmholtz equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The general theory of solutions to Laplace's equation is known as potential theory.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The twice continuously differentiable solutions of Laplace's equation are the harmonic functions, which are important in multiple branches of physics, notably electrostatics, gravitation, and fluid dynamics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In the study of heat conduction, the Laplace equation is the steady-state heat equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In general, Laplace's equation describes situations of equilibrium, or those that do not depend explicitly on time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Dirichlet problem for Laplace's equation consists of finding a solution *φ* on some domain D such that *φ* on the boundary of D is equal to some given function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Since the Laplace operator appears in the heat equation, one physical interpretation of this problem is as follows: fix the temperature on the boundary of the domain according to the given specification of the boundary condition.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Allow heat to flow until a stationary state is reached in which the temperature at each point on the domain does not change anymore.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The temperature distribution in the interior will then be given by the solution to the corresponding Dirichlet problem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Neumann boundary conditions for Laplace's equation specify not the function *φ* itself on the boundary of D but its normal derivative.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Physically, this corresponds to the construction of a potential for a vector field whose effect is known at the boundary of *D* alone.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For the example of the heat equation it amounts to prescribing the heat flux through the boundary.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In particular, at an adiabatic boundary, the normal derivative of *φ* is zero.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Solutions of Laplace's equation are called harmonic functions; they are all analytic within the domain where the equation is satisfied.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] If any two functions are solutions to Laplace's equation (or any linear homogeneous differential equation), their sum (or any linear combination) is also a solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This property, called the principle of superposition, is very useful.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For example, solutions to complex problems can be constructed by summing simple solutions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For a domain $D\subset \mathbf {R} ^{n}$ , the most common boundary value problems for Laplace's equation are the Dirichlet problem, in which the boundary values of the unknown function are prescribed, and the Neumann problem, in which its outward normal derivative is prescribed.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] If D is bounded and connected, then a harmonic function is uniquely determined by its Dirichlet boundary values; this follows from the maximum principle.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For the Neumann problem, uniqueness holds only up to an additive constant.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In special domains, solutions can be written explicitly by integral formulas.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A classical approach to the Dirichlet problem for Laplace's equation is the Perron method, which constructs a candidate solution as the supremum of all subharmonic functions lying below the prescribed boundary data.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The resulting Perron solution is harmonic in the domain; the subtle question is whether it attains the desired boundary values at every boundary point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This leads to the notion of a regular *boundary point*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A boundary point is regular if the solution of the Dirichlet problem converges to the prescribed boundary value there.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A sufficient condition is the existence of a *barrier* at that point, namely a superharmonic function that vanishes at the point and is positive elsewhere near the boundary.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For Laplace's equation, regularity of boundary points is characterized by the classical *Wiener criterion*, which gives a necessary and sufficient condition in terms of capacity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In this way, solvability of the Dirichlet problem is tied to the fine geometric structure of the boundary.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Laplace's equation can also be interpreted in a weak sense.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A function $u\in H_{\mathrm {loc} }^{1}(\Omega )$ is called **weakly harmonic** if $\int _{\Omega }\nabla u\cdot \nabla \varphi \,dx=0$ for every test function $\varphi \in C_{c}^{\infty }(\Omega )$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] By Weyl's lemma, every weakly harmonic function is in fact smooth, and indeed real analytic.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Harmonic functions also admit a variational characterization.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Among functions with fixed boundary values, the solutions of Laplace's equation are exactly the minimizers of the Dirichlet energy $E(u)={\frac {1}{2}}\int _{\Omega }|\nabla u|^{2}\,dx.$ This is known as Dirichlet's principle.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A classical symmetry of Laplace's equation is inversion in the unit sphere.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Kelvin transform is useful for converting interior problems into exterior problems, for studying isolated singularities, and for analyzing the behavior of harmonic functions at infinity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The real and imaginary parts of a complex analytic function both satisfy the Laplace equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A similar calculation shows that *v* also satisfies the Laplace equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Conversely, given a harmonic function, it is the real part of an analytic function, *f*(*z*) (at least locally).
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The integrability condition and Stokes' theorem implies that the value of the line integral connecting two points is independent of the path.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The resulting pair of solutions of the Laplace equation are called **conjugate harmonic functions**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This construction is only valid locally, or provided that the path does not loop around a singularity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] However, the angle θ is single-valued only in a region that does not enclose the origin.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The close connection between the Laplace equation and analytic functions implies that any solution of the Laplace equation has derivatives of all orders, and can be expanded in a power series, at least inside a circle that does not enclose a singularity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This is in sharp contrast to solutions of the wave equation, which generally have less regularity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] There is an intimate connection between power series and Fourier series.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] These trigonometric functions can themselves be expanded, using multiple angle formulae.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Let the quantities *u* and *v* be the horizontal and vertical components of the velocity field of a steady incompressible, irrotational flow in two dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The first derivatives of *ψ* are given by $\psi _{x}=-v,\quad \psi _{y}=u,$ and the irrotationality condition implies that *ψ* satisfies the Laplace equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The harmonic function *φ* that is conjugate to *ψ* is called the velocity potential.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Cauchy–Riemann equations imply that $\varphi _{x}=\psi _{y}=u,\quad \varphi _{y}=-\psi _{x}=v.$ Thus every analytic function corresponds to a steady incompressible, irrotational, inviscid fluid flow in the plane.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The real part is the velocity potential, and the imaginary part is the stream function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] According to Maxwell's equations, an electric field (*u*, *v*) in two space dimensions that is independent of time satisfies $\nabla \times (u,v,0)=(v_{x}-u_{y}){\hat {\mathbf {k} }}=\mathbf {0} ,$ and $\nabla \cdot (u,v)=\rho ,$ where *ρ* is the charge density.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Laplace equation can be used in three-dimensional problems in electrostatics and fluid flow just as in two dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A fundamental solution of Laplace's equation satisfies $\Delta u=u_{xx}+u_{yy}+u_{zz}=-\delta (x-x',y-y',z-z'),$ where the Dirac delta function *δ* denotes a unit source concentrated at the point (*x*′, *y*′, *z*′).
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] No function has this property: in fact it is a distribution rather than a function; but it can be thought of as a limit of functions whose integrals over space are unity, and whose support (the region where the function is non-zero) shrinks to a point (see weak solution).
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] It is common to take a different sign convention for this equation than one typically does when defining fundamental solutions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This choice of sign is often convenient to work with because −Δ is a positive operator.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Laplace equation is unchanged under a rotation of coordinates, and hence we can expect that a fundamental solution may be obtained among solutions that only depend upon the distance r from the source point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Note that, with the opposite sign convention (used in physics), this is the potential generated by a point particle, for an inverse-square law force, arising in the solution of the Poisson equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A similar argument shows that in two dimensions $u=-{\frac {\log(r)}{2\pi }}.$ where log(*r*) denotes the natural logarithm.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Note that, with the opposite sign convention, this is the potential generated by a pointlike sink (see point particle), which is the solution of the Euler equations in two-dimensional incompressible flow.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A Green's function is a fundamental solution that also satisfies a suitable condition on the boundary S of a volume V.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The notations *un* and *Gn* denote normal derivatives on *S*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Thus the Green's function describes the influence at (*x*′, *y*′, *z*′) of the data *f* and *g*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Note that if *P* is inside the sphere, then *P′* will be outside the sphere.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The Green's function is then given by ${\frac {1}{4\pi R}}-{\frac {a}{4\pi \rho R'}},\,$ where R denotes the distance to the source point *P* and *R*′ denotes the distance to the reflected point *P*′.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A consequence of this expression for the Green's function is the **Poisson integral formula**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Let ρ, θ, and φ be spherical coordinates for the source point *P*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Here θ denotes the angle with the vertical axis, which is contrary to the usual American mathematical notation, but agrees with standard European and physical practice.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Then the solution of the Laplace equation with Dirichlet boundary values *g* inside the sphere is given by (Zachmanoglou & Thoe 1986, p.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A simple consequence of this formula is that if *u* is a harmonic function, then the value of *u* at the center of the sphere is the mean value of its values on the sphere.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This mean value property immediately implies that a non-constant harmonic function cannot assume its maximum value at an interior point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The second equation can be simplified under the assumption that *Y* has the form *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) = Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*).
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A priori, *m* is a complex constant, but because Φ must be a periodic function whose period evenly divides 2*π*, *m* is necessarily an integer and Φ is a linear combination of the complex exponentials *e*±*imφ*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The solution function *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is regular at the poles of the sphere, where *θ* = 0, *π*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Furthermore, a change of variables *t* = cos *θ* transforms this equation into the Legendre equation, whose solution is a multiple of the associated Legendre polynomial *Pℓm*(cos *θ*) .
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Finally, the equation for *R* has solutions of the form *R*(*r*) = *A rℓ* + *B r*−*ℓ* − 1; requiring the solution to be regular throughout **R**3 forces *B* = 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Here the solution was assumed to have the special form *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) = Θ(*θ*) Φ(*φ*).
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For a given value of *ℓ*, there are 2*ℓ* + 1 independent solutions of this form, one for each integer *m* with −*ℓ* ≤ *m* ≤ *ℓ*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Here *Yℓm* is called a spherical harmonic function of degree ℓ and order m, *Pℓm* is an associated Legendre polynomial, *N* is a normalization constant, and θ and φ represent colatitude and longitude, respectively.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In particular, the colatitude θ, or polar angle, ranges from 0 at the North Pole, to *π*/2 at the Equator, to *π* at the South Pole, and the longitude φ, or azimuth, may assume all values with 0 ≤ *φ* < 2*π*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For a fixed integer ℓ, every solution *Y*(*θ*, *φ*) of the eigenvalue problem $r^{2}\nabla ^{2}Y=-\ell (\ell +1)Y$ is a linear combination of *Yℓm*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In fact, for any such solution, *rℓ Y*(*θ*, *φ*) is the expression in spherical coordinates of a homogeneous polynomial that is harmonic (see below), and so counting dimensions shows that there are 2*ℓ* + 1 linearly independent such polynomials.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] For $r>R$ , the solid harmonics with negative powers of r are chosen instead.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In that case, one needs to expand the solution of known regions in Laurent series (about $r=\infty$ ), instead of Taylor series (about $r=0$ ), to match the terms and find $f_{\ell }^{m}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Let $\mathbf {E}$ be the electric field, $\rho$ be the electric charge density, and $\varepsilon _{0}$ be the permittivity of free space.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Now, the electric field can be expressed as the negative gradient of the electric potential V , $\mathbf {E} =-\nabla V,$ if the field is irrotational, $\nabla \times \mathbf {E} =\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The irrotationality of $\mathbf {E}$ is also known as the electrostatic condition.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In the particular case of a source-free region, $\rho =0$ and Poisson's equation reduces to Laplace's equation for the electric potential.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] If the electrostatic potential V is specified on the boundary of a region ${\mathcal {R}}$ , then it is uniquely determined.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] If ${\mathcal {R}}$ is surrounded by a conducting material with a specified charge density $\rho$ , and if the total charge Q is known, then V is also unique.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] A potential that does not satisfy Laplace's equation together with the boundary condition is an invalid electrostatic or magnetic scalar potential.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Let $\mathbf {g}$ be the gravitational field, $\rho$ the mass density, and G the gravitational constant.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Using the differential form of Gauss's law of gravitation, we have $\nabla ^{2}V=4\pi G\rho ,$ which is Poisson's equation for gravitational fields.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In empty space, $\rho =0$ and we have $\nabla ^{2}V=0,$ which is Laplace's equation for gravitational fields.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] There is a probabilistic interpretation of Laplace's equation in terms of Brownian motion.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Let $D\subset \mathbf {R} ^{n}$ be a bounded domain, let $B_{t}$ be Brownian motion started at a point $x\in D$ , and let $\tau _{D}=\inf\{t>0:B_{t}\notin D\}$ be its first exit time from D .
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] If u is harmonic in D and extends continuously to ${\overline {D}}$ , then $u(x)=\mathbf {E} _{x}\!\left[u(B_{\tau _{D}})\right].$ This is known as Kakutani's formula.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] It expresses the value of a harmonic function at an interior point as the expected value of its boundary data at the random point where Brownian motion first exits the domain.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The distribution of the exit point $B_{\tau _{D}}$ on $\partial D$ is called the harmonic measure of D .
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Thus harmonic measure gives a probabilistic solution of the Dirichlet problem: the harmonic extension of a boundary function is obtained by averaging the boundary values against the exit distribution of Brownian motion.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] This probabilistic viewpoint also gives short proofs of several basic properties of harmonic functions, including the mean value property, the maximum principle, and uniqueness for the Dirichlet problem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In this way, harmonic measure encodes the influence of the boundary values on the interior solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] In classical domains such as the disk or ball, harmonic measure is absolutely continuous with respect to surface measure, and its density is the Poisson kernel.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Probabilistically, the harmonic measure is the distribution of the point where Brownian motion started at x first exits the domain.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Persides solved the Laplace equation in Schwarzschild spacetime on hypersurfaces of constant t.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] Here *Pl* and *Ql* are Legendre functions of the first and second kind, respectively, while *rs* is the Schwarzschild radius.
[src:partial-differential-equations/laplace-s-equation] The parameter l is an arbitrary non-negative integer.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] In mathematics, the **method of characteristics** is a technique for solving particular partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Typically, it applies to first-order equations, though in general characteristic curves can also be found for hyperbolic and parabolic partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] The method is to reduce a partial differential equation (PDE) to a family of ordinary differential equations (ODEs) along which the solution can be integrated from some initial data given on a suitable hypersurface.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] For a first-order PDE, the method of characteristics discovers so called **characteristic curves** along which the PDE becomes an ODE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Once the ODE is found, it can be solved along the characteristic curves and transformed into a solution for the original PDE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] For the sake of simplicity, we initially direct our attention to the case of a function of two independent variables *x* and *y*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] In other words, the graph of the solution to (**1**) is the union of integral curves of the vector field (**2**).
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] For this PDE to be linear, the coefficients *a**i* may be functions of the spatial variables only, and independent of *u*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] For it to be quasilinear, *a**i* may also depend on the value of the function, but not on any derivatives.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] The distinction between these two cases is inessential for the discussion here.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Equations (**4**) and (**5**) give the characteristics of the PDE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] The second equation follows from applying the chain rule to a solution *u*, and the third follows by taking an exterior derivative of the relation $du-\sum _{i}p_{i}\,dx_{i}=0$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Geometrically, the method of characteristics in the fully nonlinear case can be interpreted as requiring that the Monge cone of the differential equation should everywhere be tangent to the graph of the solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] As an example, consider the advection equation (this example assumes familiarity with PDE notation, and solutions to basic ODEs).
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] where a is constant and u is a function of x and t .
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] where $(x(s),t(s))$ is a characteristic line.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] which is the left hand side of the PDE we started with.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] So, along the characteristic line $(x(s),t(s))$ , the original PDE becomes the ODE $u_{s}=F(u,x(s),t(s))=0$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] That is to say that along the characteristics, the solution is constant.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] In this case, the characteristic lines are straight lines with slope a , and the value of u remains constant along any characteristic line.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] where the *ξ**i* are the fiber coordinates on the cotangent bundle induced by the coordinate differentials *dx**i*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Although this is defined using a particular coordinate system, the transformation law relating the *ξ**i* and the *x**i* ensures that *σ**P* is a well-defined function on the cotangent bundle.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] The function *σ**P* is homogeneous of degree *k* in the *ξ* variable.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] The zeros of *σ**P*, away from the zero section of T∗*X*, are the characteristics of *P*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Invariantly, a characteristic hypersurface is a hypersurface whose conormal bundle is in the characteristic set of *P*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Characteristics are also a powerful tool for gaining qualitative insight into a PDE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] One can use the crossings of the characteristics to find shock waves for potential flow in a compressible fluid.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Intuitively, we can think of each characteristic line implying a solution to u along itself.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Thus, when two characteristics cross, the function becomes multi-valued resulting in a non-physical solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Physically, this contradiction is removed by the formation of a shock wave, a tangential discontinuity or a weak discontinuity and can result in non-potential flow, violating the initial assumptions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] Characteristics may fail to cover part of the domain of the PDE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] This is called a rarefaction, and indicates the solution typically exists only in a weak, i.e. integral equation, sense.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] The direction of the characteristic lines indicates the flow of values through the solution, as the example above demonstrates.
[src:partial-differential-equations/method-of-characteristics] This kind of knowledge is useful when solving PDEs numerically as it can indicate which finite difference scheme is best for the problem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The **Navier–Stokes equations** (/nævˈjeɪ ˈstoʊks/ *nav-YAY STOHKS*) describe the motion of viscous fluids.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This system of partial differential equations was named after Claude-Louis Navier and George Gabriel Stokes, who developed them over a few decades of progressive work, from 1822 (Navier) to 1842–1850 (Stokes).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Siméon Denis Poisson independently achieved the same results.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations mathematically express momentum balance for Newtonian fluids and make use of the conservation of mass.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] They are sometimes accompanied by an equation of state relating pressure, temperature and density.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] They arise from applying Newton's second law to fluid motion, together with the assumption that the stress in the fluid is the sum of a diffusing viscous term (proportional to the gradient of velocity) and a pressure term—hence describing *viscous flow*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations generalize the Euler equations in that the latter model only considers inviscid flow.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations are of great scientific and engineering interest because they may be used to model a wide variety of scenarios.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In their full or simplified forms, they can assist in the design of aircraft and cars, the study of blood flow, the design of power stations, the analysis of pollution, and many other problems.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Coupled with Maxwell's equations, they comprise the fundamentals of magnetohydrodynamics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations are also of great interest in a purely mathematical sense.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Despite their wide range of practical uses, the conjecture that they have smooth (meaning infinitely differentiable) or bounded solutions in three dimensions has not yet been proven.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This is called the Navier–Stokes existence and smoothness problem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Clay Mathematics Institute has called this one of the seven most important open problems in mathematics and has offered a $1 million prize for a solution or a counterexample.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The solution of the equations is a flow velocity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] It is a vector field—to every point in a fluid, at any moment in a time interval, it gives a vector whose direction and magnitude are those of the velocity of the fluid at that point in space and at that moment in time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] It is studied in three spatial dimensions and one time dimension, and higher-dimensional analogues are studied in both pure and applied mathematics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Once the velocity field is calculated, other quantities of interest, such as pressure or temperature, may be found using dynamical equations and relations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This is different from what one normally sees in classical mechanics, where solutions are typically trajectories of the position of a particle or deflection of a continuum.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Studying velocity instead of position makes more sense for a fluid, although for visualization purposes, one can compute various trajectories.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In particular, the streamlines of a vector field, interpreted as flow velocity, are the paths along which a massless fluid particle would travel.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] These paths are the integral curves whose derivative at each point is equal to the vector field, and they can represent visually the behavior of the vector field at a point in time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In this form, it is apparent that in the assumption of an inviscid fluid – no deviatoric stress – Cauchy equations reduce to the Euler equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] to arrive at the conservation form of the equations of motion.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The left side of the equation describes acceleration, and may be composed of time-dependent and convective components (also the effects of non-inertial coordinates if present).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The right side of the equation is in effect a summation of hydrostatic effects, the divergence of deviatoric stress and body forces (such as gravity).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] All non-relativistic balance equations, such as the Navier–Stokes equations, can be derived by beginning with the Cauchy equations and specifying the stress tensor through a constitutive relation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] By expressing the deviatoric (shear) stress tensor in terms of viscosity and the fluid velocity gradient, and assuming constant viscosity, the above Cauchy equations will lead to the Navier–Stokes equations below.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] A significant feature of the Cauchy equation and consequently all other continuum equations (including Euler and Navier–Stokes) is the presence of convective acceleration: the effect of acceleration of a flow with respect to space.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] While individual fluid particles indeed experience time-dependent acceleration, the convective acceleration of the flow field is a spatial effect, one example being fluid speeding up in a nozzle.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Remark: here, the deviatoric stress tensor is denoted ${\textstyle {\boldsymbol {\tau }}}$ as it was in the general continuum equations and in the incompressible flow section.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Both bulk viscosity ${\textstyle \zeta }$ and dynamic viscosity ${\textstyle \mu }$ need not be constant – in general, they depend on two thermodynamics variables if the fluid contains a single chemical species, say for example, pressure and temperature.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Any equation that makes explicit one of these transport coefficient in the conservation variables is called an equation of state.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Apart from its dependence of pressure and temperature, the second viscosity coefficient also depends on the process, that is to say, the second viscosity coefficient is not just a material property.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Example: in the case of a sound wave with a definitive frequency that alternatively compresses and expands a fluid element, the second viscosity coefficient depends on the frequency of the wave.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This dependence is called the *dispersion*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The assumption of setting ${\textstyle \zeta =0}$ is called as the **Stokes hypothesis**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The validity of Stokes hypothesis can be demonstrated for monoatomic gas both experimentally and from the kinetic theory; for other gases and liquids, Stokes hypothesis is generally incorrect.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] If the dynamic $\mu$ and bulk $\zeta$ viscosities are assumed to be uniform in space, the equations in convective form can be simplified further.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where ${\textstyle {\frac {\mathrm {D} }{\mathrm {D} t}}}$ is the material derivative. ${\textstyle \nu ={\frac {\mu }{\rho }}}$ is the shear kinematic viscosity and ${\textstyle \xi ={\frac {\zeta }{\rho }}}$ is the bulk kinematic viscosity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The left-hand side changes in the conservation form of the Navier–Stokes momentum equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The convective acceleration term can also be written as $\mathbf {u} \cdot \nabla \mathbf {u} =(\nabla \times \mathbf {u} )\times \mathbf {u} +{\tfrac {1}{2}}\nabla \mathbf {u} ^{2},$ where the vector ${\textstyle (\nabla \times \mathbf {u} )\times \mathbf {u} }$ is known as the Lamb vector.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] For the special case of an incompressible flow, the pressure constrains the flow so that the volume of fluid elements is constant: isochoric flow resulting in a solenoidal velocity field with ${\textstyle \nabla \cdot \mathbf {u} =0}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This is constitutive equation is also called the **Newtonian law of viscosity**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Dynamic viscosity μ need not be constant – in incompressible flows it can depend on density and on pressure.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Any equation that makes explicit one of these transport coefficient in the conservative variables is called an equation of state.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Incompressibility rules out density and pressure waves like sound or shock waves, so this simplification is not useful if these phenomena are of interest.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where ${\textstyle \nu ={\frac {\mu }{\rho }}}$ is called the kinematic viscosity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where ${\textstyle {\frac {p}{\rho }}}$ is called the unit pressure head.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] which is obtained by taking the divergence of the momentum equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The higher-order term, namely the shear stress divergence ${\textstyle \nabla \cdot {\boldsymbol {\tau }}}$ , has simply reduced to the vector Laplacian term ${\textstyle \mu \nabla ^{2}\mathbf {u} }$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This Laplacian term can be interpreted as the difference between the velocity at a point and the mean velocity in a small surrounding volume.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This implies that – for a Newtonian fluid – viscosity operates as a *diffusion of momentum*, in much the same way as the heat conduction.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In fact neglecting the convection term, incompressible Navier–Stokes equations lead to a vector diffusion equation (namely Stokes equations), but in general the convection term is present, so incompressible Navier–Stokes equations belong to the class of convection–diffusion equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The incompressible Navier–Stokes equations with uniform density and viscosity and conservative external field is the **fundamental equation of hydraulics**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The domain for these equations is commonly a 3 or fewer dimensional Euclidean space, for which an orthogonal coordinate reference frame is usually set to explicit the system of scalar partial differential equations to be solved.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In 3-dimensional orthogonal coordinate systems are 3: Cartesian, cylindrical, and spherical.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] But for the higher order terms (the two coming from the divergence of the deviatoric stress that distinguish Navier–Stokes equations from Euler equations) some tensor calculus is required for deducing an expression in non-cartesian orthogonal coordinate systems.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] A special case of the fundamental equation of hydraulics is the Bernoulli's equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This result follows from the Helmholtz theorem (also known as the fundamental theorem of vector calculus).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The first equation is a pressureless governing equation for the velocity, while the second equation for the pressure is a functional of the velocity and is related to the pressure Poisson equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Thus the governing equation is an integro-differential equation similar to Coulomb's and Biot–Savart's law, not convenient for numerical computation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] for divergence-free test functions ${\textstyle \mathbf {w} }$ satisfying appropriate boundary conditions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Here, the projections are accomplished by the orthogonality of the solenoidal and irrotational function spaces.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The discrete form of this is eminently suited to finite element computation of divergence-free flow, as we shall see in the next section.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] There, one will be able to address the question, "How does one specify pressure-driven (Poiseuille) problems with a pressureless governing equation?".
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The absence of pressure forces from the governing velocity equation demonstrates that the equation is not a dynamic one, but rather a kinematic equation where the divergence-free condition serves the role of a conservation equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This would seem to refute the frequent statements that the incompressible pressure enforces the divergence-free condition.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The first equation is the momentum balance equation, while the second represents the mass conservation, namely the continuity equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] It is desirable to choose basis functions that reflect the essential feature of incompressible flow – the elements must be divergence-free.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] While the velocity is the variable of interest, the existence of the stream function or vector potential is necessary by the Helmholtz theorem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Further, to determine fluid flow in the absence of a pressure gradient, one can specify the difference of stream function values across a 2D channel, or the line integral of the tangential component of the vector potential around the channel in 3D, the flow being given by Stokes' theorem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Discussion will be restricted to 2D in the following.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] We further restrict discussion to continuous Hermite finite elements which have at least first-derivative degrees-of-freedom.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] With this, one can draw a large number of candidate triangular and rectangular elements from the plate-bending literature.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] These elements have derivatives as components of the gradient.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Adopting continuous plate-bending elements, interchanging the derivative degrees-of-freedom and changing the sign of the appropriate one gives many families of stream function elements.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Taking the curl of the scalar stream function elements gives divergence-free velocity elements.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The requirement that the stream function elements be continuous assures that the normal component of the velocity is continuous across element interfaces, all that is necessary for vanishing divergence on these interfaces.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Boundary conditions are simple to apply.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The stream function is constant on no-flow surfaces, with no-slip velocity conditions on surfaces.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Stream function differences across open channels determine the flow.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] No boundary conditions are necessary on open boundaries, though consistent values may be used with some problems.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The algebraic equations to be solved are simple to set up, but of course are non-linear, requiring iteration of the linearized equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Similar considerations apply to three-dimensions, but extension from 2D is not immediate because of the vector nature of the potential, and there exists no simple relation between the gradient and the curl as was the case in 2D.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Recovering pressure from the velocity field is easy.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] where the test/weight functions are irrotational.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Any conforming scalar finite element may be used.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] However, the pressure gradient field may also be of interest.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] In this case, one can use scalar Hermite elements for the pressure.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] For the test/weight functions ${\textstyle \mathbf {g} _{i}}$ one would choose the irrotational vector elements obtained from the gradient of the pressure element.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The rotating frame of reference introduces some interesting pseudo-forces into the equations through the material derivative term.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Consider a stationary inertial frame of reference ${\textstyle K}$ , and a non-inertial frame of reference ${\textstyle K'}$ , which is translating with velocity ${\textstyle \mathbf {U} (t)}$ and rotating with angular velocity ${\textstyle \Omega (t)}$ with respect to the stationary frame.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Here ${\textstyle \mathbf {x} }$ and ${\textstyle \mathbf {u} }$ are measured in the non-inertial frame.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] The Navier–Stokes equations are strictly a statement of the balance of momentum.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] To fully describe fluid flow, more information is needed, how much depending on the assumptions made.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] This additional information may include boundary data (no-slip, capillary surface, etc.), conservation of mass, balance of energy, and/or an equation of state.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Regardless of the flow assumptions, a statement of the conservation of mass is generally necessary.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p01] Therefore, the rate of change of $\rho$ with respect to time ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial \rho }{\partial t}}}$ and the gradient of density ${\textstyle \nabla \rho }$ are equal to zero.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Taking the curl of the incompressible Navier–Stokes equation results in the elimination of pressure.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Differentiating the first with respect to ${\textstyle y}$ , the second with respect to ${\textstyle x}$ and subtracting the resulting equations will eliminate pressure and any conservative force.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] where ${\textstyle \nabla ^{4}}$ is the 2D biharmonic operator and ${\textstyle \nu }$ is the kinematic viscosity, ${\textstyle \nu ={\frac {\mu }{\rho }}}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This single equation together with appropriate boundary conditions describes 2D fluid flow, taking only kinematic viscosity as a parameter.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Note that the equation for creeping flow results when the left side is assumed zero.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] In axisymmetric flow another stream function formulation, called the Stokes stream function, can be used to describe the velocity components of an incompressible flow with one scalar function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The incompressible Navier–Stokes equation is a differential algebraic equation, having the inconvenient feature that there is no explicit mechanism for advancing the pressure in time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Consequently, much effort has been expended to eliminate the pressure from all or part of the computational process.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The stream function formulation eliminates the pressure but only in two dimensions and at the expense of introducing higher derivatives and elimination of the velocity, which is the primary variable of interest.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The Navier–Stokes equations are nonlinear partial differential equations in the general case and so remain in almost every real situation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] In some cases, such as one-dimensional flow and Stokes flow (or creeping flow), the equations can be simplified to linear equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The nonlinearity makes most problems difficult or impossible to solve and is the main contributor to the turbulence that the equations model.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The nonlinearity is due to convective acceleration, which is an acceleration associated with the change in velocity over position.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Hence, any convective flow, whether turbulent or not, will involve nonlinearity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] An example of convective but laminar (nonturbulent) flow would be the passage of a viscous fluid (for example, oil) through a small converging nozzle.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Such flows, whether exactly solvable or not, can often be thoroughly studied and understood.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Turbulence is the time-dependent chaotic behaviour seen in many fluid flows.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] It is generally believed that it is due to the inertia of the fluid as a whole: the culmination of time-dependent and convective acceleration; hence flows where inertial effects are small tend to be laminar (the Reynolds number quantifies how much the flow is affected by inertia).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] It is believed, though not known with certainty, that the Navier–Stokes equations describe turbulence properly.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Attempts to solve turbulent flow using a laminar solver typically result in a time-unsteady solution, which fails to converge appropriately.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] To counter this, time-averaged equations such as the Reynolds-averaged Navier–Stokes equations (RANS), supplemented with turbulence models, are used in practical computational fluid dynamics (CFD) applications when modeling turbulent flows.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Some models include the Spalart–Allmaras, k–ω, k–ε, and SST models, which add a variety of additional equations to bring closure to the RANS equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Large eddy simulation (LES) can also be used to solve these equations numerically.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This approach is computationally more expensive—in time and in computer memory—than RANS, but produces better results because it explicitly resolves the larger turbulent scales.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Together with supplemental equations (for example, conservation of mass) and well-formulated boundary conditions, the Navier–Stokes equations seem to model fluid motion accurately; even turbulent flows seem (on average) to agree with real world observations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The Navier–Stokes equations assume that the fluid being studied is a continuum (it is infinitely divisible and not composed of particles such as atoms or molecules), and is not moving at relativistic velocities.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] At very small scales or under extreme conditions, real fluids made out of discrete molecules will produce results different from the continuous fluids modeled by the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For example, capillarity of internal layers in fluids appears for flow with high gradients.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For large Knudsen number of the problem, the Boltzmann equation may be a suitable replacement.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Failing that, one may have to resort to molecular dynamics or various hybrid methods.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Another limitation is simply the complicated nature of the equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Time-tested formulations exist for common fluid families, but the application of the Navier–Stokes equations to less common families tends to result in very complicated formulations and often to open research problems.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For this reason, these equations are usually written for Newtonian fluids where the viscosity model is linear; truly general models for the flow of other kinds of fluids (such as blood) do not exist.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The Navier–Stokes equations, even when written explicitly for specific fluids, are rather generic in nature and their proper application to specific problems can be very diverse.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This is partly because there is an enormous variety of problems that may be modeled, ranging from as simple as the distribution of static pressure to as complicated as multiphase flow driven by surface tension.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Generally, application to specific problems begins with some flow assumptions and initial/boundary condition formulation, this may be followed by scale analysis to further simplify the problem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The boundary condition is the no slip condition.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] From this point onward, more quantities of interest can be easily obtained, such as viscous drag force or net flow rate.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Difficulties may arise when the problem becomes slightly more complicated.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A seemingly modest twist on the parallel flow above would be the *radial* flow between parallel plates; this involves convection and thus non-linearity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This ordinary differential equation is what is obtained when the Navier–Stokes equations are written and the flow assumptions applied (additionally, the pressure gradient is solved for).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The nonlinear term makes this a very difficult problem to solve analytically (a lengthy implicit solution may be found which involves elliptic integrals and roots of cubic polynomials).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Issues with the actual existence of solutions arise for ${\textstyle R>1.41}$ (approximately; this is not √2), the parameter ${\textstyle R}$ being the Reynolds number with appropriately chosen scales.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This is an example of flow assumptions losing their applicability, and an example of the difficulty in "high" Reynolds number flows.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A type of natural convection that can be described by the Navier–Stokes equation is the Rayleigh–Bénard convection.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] It is one of the most commonly studied convection phenomena because of its analytical and experimental accessibility.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Some exact solutions to the Navier–Stokes equations exist.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Examples of degenerate cases—with the non-linear terms in the Navier–Stokes equations equal to zero—are Poiseuille flow, Couette flow and the oscillatory Stokes boundary layer.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] But also, more interesting examples, solutions to the full non-linear equations, exist, such as Jeffery–Hamel flow, Von Kármán swirling flow, stagnation point flow, Landau–Squire jet, and Taylor–Green vortex.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Time-dependent self-similar solutions of the three-dimensional non-compressible Navier–Stokes equations in Cartesian coordinate can be given with the help of the Kummer's functions with quadratic arguments.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] For the compressible Navier–Stokes equations the time-dependent self-similar solutions are however the Whittaker functions again with quadratic arguments when the polytropic equation of state is used as a closing condition.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Note that the existence of these exact solutions does not imply they are stable: turbulence may develop at higher Reynolds numbers.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Under additional assumptions, the component parts can be separated.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This solution is valid in the domain *r* ≥ 1 and for *A* < −2*ν*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] There is a singularity at *x* = *y* = *z* = 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A steady-state example with no singularities comes from considering the flow along the lines of a Hopf fibration.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Let ${\textstyle r}$ be a constant radius of the inner coil.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] for arbitrary constants ${\textstyle A}$ and ${\textstyle B}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This is a solution in a non-viscous gas (compressible fluid) whose density, velocities and pressure goes to zero far from the origin.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Two examples of periodic fully-three-dimensional viscous solutions are described in.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] These solutions are defined on a three-dimensional torus $\mathbb {T} ^{3}=[0,L]^{3}$ and are characterized by positive and negative helicity respectively.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] The pressure field is obtained from the velocity field as $p=p_{0}-\rho _{0}\|{\boldsymbol {u}}\|^{2}/2$ (where $p_{0}$ and $\rho _{0}$ are reference values for the pressure and density fields respectively).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Since both the solutions belong to the class of Beltrami flow, the vorticity field is parallel to the velocity and, for the case with positive helicity, is given by $\omega ={\sqrt {3}}\,k\,{\boldsymbol {u}}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] These solutions can be regarded as a generalization in three dimensions of the classic two-dimensional Taylor–Green vortex.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] A 2022 paper provides a less costly, dynamical and recurrent solution of the Navier-Stokes equation for 3D turbulent fluid flows.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] On suitably short time scales, the dynamics of turbulence is deterministic.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Note that gravity has been accounted for as a body force, and the values of ${\textstyle g_{x}}$ , ${\textstyle g_{y}}$ , ${\textstyle g_{z}}$ will depend on the orientation of gravity with respect to the chosen set of coordinates.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] When the flow is incompressible, ${\textstyle \rho }$ does not change for any fluid particle, and its material derivative vanishes: ${\textstyle {\frac {\mathrm {D} \rho }{\mathrm {D} t}}=0}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Thus, for the incompressible version of the Navier–Stokes equation the second part of the viscous terms fall away (see Incompressible flow).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This system of four equations comprises the most commonly used and studied form.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Though comparatively more compact than other representations, this is still a nonlinear system of partial differential equations for which solutions are difficult to obtain.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] This cylindrical representation of the incompressible Navier–Stokes equations is the second most commonly seen (the first being Cartesian above).
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] Cylindrical coordinates are chosen to take advantage of symmetry, so that a velocity component can disappear.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] These equations could be (slightly) compacted by, for example, factoring ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{r^{2}}}}$ from the viscous terms.
[src:partial-differential-equations/navier-stokes-equations-p02] However, doing so would undesirably alter the structure of the Laplacian and other quantities.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In mathematics, a **partial differential equation** (**PDE**) is an equation which involves a multivariable function and one or more of its partial derivatives.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The function is often thought of as an "unknown" that solves the equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] However, it is often impossible to write down explicit formulas for solutions of partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Hence there is a vast amount of modern mathematical and scientific research on methods to numerically approximate solutions of partial differential equations using computers.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Partial differential equations also occupy a large sector of pure mathematical research, where the focus is on the qualitative features of solutions of various partial differential equations, such as existence, uniqueness, regularity and stability.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Among the many open questions are the existence and smoothness of solutions to the Navier–Stokes equations, named as one of the Millennium Prize Problems in 2000.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Partial differential equations occur very widely in mathematically oriented scientific fields, such as physics and engineering.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] For instance, they are foundational in the modern scientific understanding of sound, heat, diffusion, electrostatics, electrodynamics, thermodynamics, fluid dynamics, elasticity, general relativity, and quantum mechanics (Schrödinger equation, Pauli equation etc.).
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] They also arise from many purely mathematical considerations, such as differential geometry and the calculus of variations; among other notable applications, they are the fundamental tool in the proof of the Poincaré conjecture from geometric topology.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Partly due to this variety of sources, there is a wide spectrum of types of partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Many different methods have been developed for dealing with the individual equations which arise.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] As such, there is no "universal theory" of partial differential equations, with specialist knowledge being divided between several distinct subfields.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Ordinary differential equations can be viewed as a subclass of partial differential equations, corresponding to functions of a single variable.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Stochastic partial differential equations and nonlocal equations are widely studied extensions of the "PDE" notion.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] More classical topics, on which there is still much active research, include elliptic and parabolic partial differential equations, fluid mechanics, Boltzmann equations, and dispersive partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] One of the most important partial differential equations, with many applications, is Laplace's equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] For a function *u*(*x*, *y*, *z*) of three variables, Laplace's equation is ${\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}}+{\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}}+{\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}}}=0.$ A function that obeys this equation is called a harmonic function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Such functions were widely studied in the 19th century due to their relevance for classical mechanics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] For example, the equilibrium temperature distribution of a homogeneous solid is a harmonic function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] It is usually a matter of straightforward computation to check whether or not a given function is harmonic.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] It may be surprising that these examples of harmonic functions are of such different forms.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This is a reflection of the fact that they are not special cases of a "general solution formula" of Laplace's equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This is in striking contrast to the case of many ordinary differential equations (ODEs), where many introductory textbooks aim to find methods leading to general solutions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] For Laplace's equation, as for a large number of partial differential equations, such solution formulas do not exist.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This is far beyond the choices available in ODE solution formulas, which typically only allow the free choice of some constants.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In the study of PDEs, one generally has the free choice of functions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The nature of this choice varies from PDE to PDE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] To understand it for any given equation, existence and uniqueness theorems are usually important organizational principles.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] By contrast, for PDEs, existence and uniqueness theorems are often the only means by which one can navigate through the plethora of different solutions at hand.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] For this reason, they are also fundamental when carrying out a purely numerical simulation, as one must have an understanding of what data is to be prescribed by the user and what is to be left to the computer to calculate.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] To discuss such existence and uniqueness theorems, it is necessary to be precise about the domain of the "unknown function".
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Otherwise, speaking only in terms such as "a function of two variables", it is impossible to meaningfully formulate the results.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] That is, the domain of the unknown function must be regarded as part of the structure of the PDE itself.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The following provides two classic examples of such existence and uniqueness theorems.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Even though the two PDEs in question are so similar, there is a major difference in behavior: for the first PDE, one has the free prescription of a single function, while for the second PDE, one has the free prescription of two functions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] For instance, the following PDE, arising naturally in the field of differential geometry, illustrates an example where there is a simple and completely explicit solution formula, but with the free choice of only three numbers and not even one function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In contrast to the earlier examples, this PDE is **nonlinear**, owing to the square roots and the squares.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] A **linear** PDE is one such that, if it is homogeneous, the sum of any two solutions is also a solution, and any constant multiple of any solution is also a solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] A partial differential equation is an equation that involves an unknown function of $n\geq 2$ variables and (some of) its partial derivatives.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] For multiple derivatives, multi-index notation can be used.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] A PDE is called **linear** if it is linear in the unknown and its derivatives.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] (Often the mixed-partial derivatives *uxy* and *uyx* will be equated, but this is not required for the discussion of linearity.) If the *ai* are constants (independent of x and y) then the PDE is called **linear with constant coefficients**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] If *f* is zero everywhere then the linear PDE is **homogeneous**, otherwise it is **inhomogeneous**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Nearest to linear PDEs are **semi-linear** PDEs, where only the highest order derivatives appear as linear terms, with coefficients that are functions of the independent variables.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The lower order derivatives and the unknown function may appear arbitrarily.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] A PDE without any linearity properties is called **fully nonlinear**, and possesses nonlinearities on one or more of the highest-order derivatives.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] An example is the Monge–Ampère equation, which arises in differential geometry.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The elliptic/parabolic/hyperbolic classification provides a guide to appropriate initial- and boundary conditions and to the smoothness of the solutions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Assuming *uxy* = *uyx*, the general linear second-order PDE in two independent variables has the form $Au_{xx}+2Bu_{xy}+Cu_{yy}+\cdots {\mbox{(lower order terms)}}=0,$ where the coefficients A, B, C... may depend upon x and y.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] If *A*2 + *B*2 + *C*2 > 0 over a region of the xy-plane, the PDE is second-order in that region.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Just as one classifies conic sections and quadratic forms into parabolic, hyperbolic, and elliptic based on the discriminant *B*2 − 4*AC*, the same can be done for a second-order PDE at a given point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] However, the discriminant in a PDE is given by *B*2 − *AC* due to the convention of the xy term being 2*B* rather than B; formally, the discriminant (of the associated quadratic form) is (2*B*)2 − 4*AC* = 4(*B*2 − *AC*), with the factor of 4 dropped for simplicity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] *B*2 − *AC* = 0 (*parabolic partial differential equation*): Equations that are parabolic at every point can be transformed into a form analogous to the heat equation by a change of independent variables.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Solutions smooth out as the transformed time variable increases.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The Euler–Tricomi equation has parabolic type on the line where *x* = 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] By change of variables, the equation can always be expressed in the form: $u_{xx}+\cdots =0,$ where x correspond to changed variables.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This justifies the heat equation, which is of the form ${\textstyle u_{t}-u_{xx}+\cdots =0}$ , as an example of this type.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] *B*2 − *AC* > 0 (*hyperbolic partial differential equation*): hyperbolic equations retain any discontinuities of functions or derivatives in the initial data.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The motion of a fluid at supersonic speeds can be approximated with hyperbolic PDEs, and the Euler–Tricomi equation is hyperbolic where *x* > 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] By change of variables, the equation can always be expressed in the form: $u_{xx}-u_{yy}+\cdots =0,$ where x and y correspond to changed variables.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This justifies the wave equation as an example of this type.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The classification depends upon the signature of the eigenvalues of the coefficient matrix *a**i*,*j*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Parabolic: the eigenvalues are all positive or all negative, except one that is zero.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Hyperbolic: there is only one negative eigenvalue and all the rest are positive, or there is only one positive eigenvalue and all the rest are negative.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Ultrahyperbolic: there is more than one positive eigenvalue and more than one negative eigenvalue, and there are no zero eigenvalues.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The theory of elliptic, parabolic, and hyperbolic equations have been studied for centuries, largely centered around or based upon the standard examples of the Laplace equation, the heat equation, and the wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] However, the classification only depends on linearity of the second-order terms and is therefore applicable to semi- and quasilinear PDEs as well.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The basic types also extend to hybrids such as the Euler–Tricomi equation; varying from elliptic to hyperbolic for different regions of the domain, as well as higher-order PDEs, but such knowledge is more specialized.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The classification of partial differential equations can be extended to systems of first-order equations, where the unknown u is now a vector with m components, and the coefficient matrices Aν are m by m matrices for *ν* = 1, 2, …, *n*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The partial differential equation takes the form $Lu=\sum _{\nu =1}^{n}A_{\nu }{\frac {\partial u}{\partial x_{\nu }}}+B=0,$ where the coefficient matrices Aν and the vector B may depend upon x and u.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The geometric interpretation of this condition is as follows: if data for u are prescribed on the surface S, then it may be possible to determine the normal derivative of u on S from the differential equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] If the data on S and the differential equation determine the normal derivative of u on S, then S is non-characteristic.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] If the data on S and the differential equation *do not* determine the normal derivative of u on S, then the surface is **characteristic**, and the differential equation restricts the data on S: the differential equation is *internal* to S.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] A first-order system is *hyperbolic* at a point if there is a **spacelike** surface S with normal ξ at that point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This means that, given any non-trivial vector η orthogonal to ξ, and a scalar multiplier λ, the equation *Q*(*λξ* + *η*) = 0 has m real roots *λ*1, *λ*2, …, *λ**m*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The system is **strictly hyperbolic** if these roots are always distinct.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The geometrical interpretation of this condition is as follows: the characteristic form *Q*(*ζ*) = 0 defines a cone (the normal cone) with homogeneous coordinates ζ.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In the hyperbolic case, this cone has nm sheets, and the axis *ζ* = *λξ* runs inside these sheets: it does not intersect any of them.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] But when displaced from the origin by η, this axis intersects every sheet.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In the elliptic case, the normal cone has no real sheets.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Linear PDEs can be reduced to systems of ordinary differential equations by the important technique of separation of variables.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This technique rests on a feature of solutions to differential equations: if one can find any solution that solves the equation and satisfies the boundary conditions, then it is *the* solution (this also applies to ODEs).
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] We assume as an ansatz that the dependence of a solution on the parameters space and time can be written as a product of terms that each depend on a single parameter, and then see if this can be made to solve the problem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In the method of separation of variables, one reduces a PDE to a PDE in fewer variables, which is an ordinary differential equation if in one variable – these are in turn easier to solve.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This is possible for simple PDEs, which are called separable partial differential equations, and the domain is generally a rectangle (a product of intervals).
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Separable PDEs correspond to diagonal matrices – thinking of "the value for fixed x" as a coordinate, each coordinate can be understood separately.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This generalizes to the method of characteristics, and is also used in integral transforms.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The characteristic surface in *n* = *2*-dimensional space is called a **characteristic curve**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In special cases, one can find characteristic curves on which the first-order PDE reduces to an ODE – changing coordinates in the domain to straighten these curves allows separation of variables, and is called the method of characteristics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] More generally, applying the method to first-order PDEs in higher dimensions, one may find characteristic surfaces.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] An integral transform may transform the PDE to a simpler one, in particular, a separable PDE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This corresponds to diagonalizing an operator.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] An important example of this is Fourier analysis, which diagonalizes the heat equation using the eigenbasis of sinusoidal waves.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] If the domain is finite or periodic, an infinite sum of solutions such as a Fourier series is appropriate, but an integral of solutions such as a Fourier integral is generally required for infinite domains.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The solution for a point source for the heat equation given above is an example of the use of a Fourier integral.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Often a PDE can be reduced to a simpler form with a known solution by a suitable change of variables.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Inhomogeneous equations can often be solved (for constant coefficient PDEs, always be solved) by finding the fundamental solution (the solution for a point source $P(D)u=\delta$ ), then taking the convolution with the boundary conditions to get the solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This is analogous in signal processing to understanding a filter by its impulse response.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The superposition principle applies to any linear system, including linear systems of PDEs.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] A common visualization of this concept is the interaction of two waves in phase being combined to result in a greater amplitude, for example sin *x* + sin *x* = 2 sin *x*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The same principle can be observed in PDEs where the solutions may be real or complex and additive.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] If *u*1 and *u*2 are solutions of linear PDE in some function space R, then *u* = *c*1*u*1 + *c*2*u*2 with any constants *c*1 and *c*2 are also a solution of that PDE in the same function space.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] There are no generally applicable analytical methods to solve nonlinear PDEs.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Still, existence and uniqueness results (such as the Cauchy–Kowalevski theorem) are often possible, as are proofs of important qualitative and quantitative properties of solutions (getting these results is a major part of analysis).
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Nevertheless, some techniques can be used for several types of equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The h-principle is the most powerful method to solve underdetermined equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The Riquier–Janet theory is an effective method for obtaining information about many analytic overdetermined systems.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The method of characteristics can be used in some very special cases to solve nonlinear partial differential equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In some cases, a PDE can be solved via perturbation analysis in which the solution is considered to be a correction to an equation with a known solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Alternatives are numerical analysis techniques from simple finite difference schemes to the more mature multigrid and finite element methods.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Many interesting problems in science and engineering are solved in this way using computers, sometimes high performance supercomputers.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] From 1870 Sophus Lie's work put the theory of differential equations on a more satisfactory foundation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] He showed that the integration theories of the older mathematicians can, by the introduction of what are now called Lie groups, be referred, to a common source; and that ordinary differential equations which admit the same infinitesimal transformations present comparable difficulties of integration.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] He also emphasized the subject of transformations of contact.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] A general approach to solving PDEs uses the symmetry property of differential equations, the continuous infinitesimal transformations of solutions to solutions (Lie theory).
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Symmetry methods have been recognized to study differential equations arising in mathematics, physics, engineering, and many other disciplines.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The Adomian decomposition method, the Lyapunov artificial small parameter method, and his homotopy perturbation method are all special cases of the more general homotopy analysis method.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] These are series expansion methods, and except for the Lyapunov method, are independent of small physical parameters as compared to the well known perturbation theory, thus giving these methods greater flexibility and solution generality.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The three most widely used numerical methods to solve PDEs are the finite element method (FEM), finite volume methods (FVM) and finite difference methods (FDM), as well other kind of methods called meshfree methods, which were made to solve problems where the aforementioned methods are limited.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The FEM has a prominent position among these methods and especially its exceptionally efficient higher-order version hp-FEM.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The finite element method (FEM) (its practical application often known as finite element analysis (FEA)) is a numerical technique for approximating solutions of partial differential equations (PDE) as well as of integral equations using a finite set of functions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Finite-difference methods are numerical methods for approximating the solutions to differential equations using finite difference equations to approximate derivatives.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Similar to the finite difference method or finite element method, values are calculated at discrete places on a meshed geometry.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] "Finite volume" refers to the small volume surrounding each node point on a mesh.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In the finite volume method, surface integrals in a partial differential equation that contain a divergence term are converted to volume integrals, using the divergence theorem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] These terms are then evaluated as fluxes at the surfaces of each finite volume.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Because the flux entering a given volume is identical to that leaving the adjacent volume, these methods conserve mass by design.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Weak solutions are functions that satisfy the PDE, yet in other meanings than regular sense.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The meaning for this term may differ with context, and one of the most commonly used definitions is based on the notion of distributions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] In pure mathematics, the theoretical studies of PDEs focus on the criteria for a solution to exist and the properties of a solution while finding its formula is often secondary.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Well-posedness refers to a common schematic package of information about a PDE.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This is, by the necessity of being applicable to several different PDE, somewhat vague.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] The requirement of "continuity", in particular, is ambiguous, since there are usually many inequivalent means by which it can be rigorously defined.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] It is, however, somewhat unusual to study a PDE without specifying a way in which it is well-posed.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Regularity refers to the integrability and differentiability of weak solutions, which can often be represented by Sobolev spaces.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] This problem arise due to the difficulty in searching for classical solutions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Researchers often tend to find weak solutions at first and then find out whether it is smooth enough to be qualified as a classical solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/partial-differential-equation] Results from functional analysis are often used in this field of study.
