[src:partial-differential-equations/separation-of-variables] If T is a compact, self-adjoint operator on the space $L^{2}[0,l]$ along with the relevant boundary conditions, then by the Spectral theorem there exists a basis for $L^{2}[0,l]$ consisting of eigenfunctions for T .
[src:partial-differential-equations/separation-of-variables] Let the spectrum of T be E and let $f_{\lambda }$ be an eigenfunction with eigenvalue $\lambda \in E$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/separation-of-variables] Then for any function which at each time t is square-integrable with respect to x , we can write this function as a linear combination of the $f_{\lambda }$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/separation-of-variables] Hence, the spectral theorem ensures that the separation of variables will (when it is possible) find all the solutions.
