[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The **wave equation** is a second-order linear partial differential equation for the description of waves or standing wave fields such as mechanical waves (e.g. water waves, sound waves and seismic waves) or electromagnetic waves (including light waves).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] It arises in fields like acoustics, electromagnetism, and fluid dynamics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This article focuses on waves in classical physics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Quantum physics uses an operator-based wave equation often as a relativistic wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The wave equation is a hyperbolic partial differential equation describing waves, including traveling and standing waves; the latter can be considered as linear superpositions of waves traveling in opposite directions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This article mostly focuses on the scalar wave equation describing waves in scalars by scalar functions $u=u(x,y,z,t)$ of a time variable t (a variable representing time) and one or more spatial variables $x,y,z$ (variables representing a position in a space under discussion).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] At the same time, there are vector wave equations describing waves in vectors such as waves for an electrical field, magnetic field, and magnetic vector potential and elastic waves.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] For example, in the Cartesian coordinate system, for $(E_{x},E_{y},E_{z})$ as the representation of an electric vector field wave ${\vec {E}}$ in the absence of wave sources, each coordinate axis component $E_{i},i=x,y,z,$ must satisfy the scalar wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Other scalar wave equation solutions u are for physical quantities in scalars such as pressure in a liquid or gas, or the displacement along some specific direction of particles of a vibrating solid away from their resting (equilibrium) positions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The equation states that, at any given point, the second derivative of u with respect to time is proportional to the sum of the second derivatives of u with respect to space, with the constant of proportionality being the square of the speed of the wave.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] A solution to this (two-way) wave equation can be quite complicated.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Still, it can be analyzed as a linear combination of simple solutions that are sinusoidal plane waves with various directions of propagation and wavelengths but all with the same propagation speed c .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This analysis is possible because the wave equation is linear and homogeneous, so that any multiple of a solution is also a solution, and the sum of any two solutions is again a solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This property is called the superposition principle in physics.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The wave equation alone does not specify a physical solution; a unique solution is usually obtained by setting a problem with further conditions, such as initial conditions, which prescribe the amplitude and phase of the wave.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Another important class of problems occurs in enclosed spaces specified by boundary conditions, for which the solutions represent standing waves, or harmonics, analogous to the harmonics of musical instruments.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The wave equation in one spatial dimension can be written as follows: ${\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial t^{2}}}=c^{2}{\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}}.$ This equation is typically described as having only one spatial dimension x , because the only other independent variable is the time t .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The wave equation in one space dimension can be derived in a variety of different physical settings.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Most famously, it can be derived for the case of a string vibrating in a two-dimensional plane, with each of its elements being pulled in opposite directions by the force of tension.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Another physical setting for derivation of the wave equation in one space dimension uses Hooke's law.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In the theory of elasticity, Hooke's law is an approximation for certain materials, stating that the amount by which a material body is deformed (the strain) is linearly related to the force causing the deformation (the stress).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The wave equation in the one-dimensional case can be derived from Hooke's law in the following way: imagine an array of little weights of mass m interconnected with massless springs of length ⁠ h ⁠.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Here the dependent variable $u(x)$ measures the horizontal displacement from equilibrium of the mass situated at ⁠ x ⁠, so that $u(x)$ essentially measures the magnitude of a disturbance (i.e. strain) that is traveling in an elastic material.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In the case of a stress pulse propagating longitudinally through a bar, the bar acts much like an infinite number of springs in series and can be taken as an extension of the equation derived for Hooke's law.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] A uniform bar, i.e. of constant cross-section, made from a linear elastic material has a stiffness K given by $K={\frac {EA}{L}},$ where A is the cross-sectional area, and E is the Young's modulus of the material.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] $AL$ is equal to the volume of the bar, and therefore ${\frac {AL}{M}}={\frac {1}{\rho }},$ where $\rho$ is the density of the material.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The speed of a stress wave in a bar is therefore ${\sqrt {E/\rho }}$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] For the one-dimensional wave equation a relatively simple general solution may be found.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In other words, the solution is the sum of a right-traveling function F and a left-traveling function G .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] "Traveling" means that the shape of these individual arbitrary functions with respect to x stays constant, however, the functions are translated left and right with time at the speed c .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This was derived by Jean le Rond d'Alembert.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This advection equation can be solved by interpreting it as telling us that the directional derivative of v in the $(1,-c)$ direction is 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This means that the value of v is constant on characteristic lines of the form *x* + *ct* = *x*0, and thus that v must depend only on *x* + *ct*, that is, have the form *H*(*x* + *ct*).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Then, to solve the first (inhomogenous) equation relating v to u, we can note that its homogenous solution must be a function of the form *F*(*x* - *ct*), by logic similar to the above.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This means we can find a particular solution *G* of the desired form by integration.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] However, the waveforms F and G may also be generalized functions, such as the delta-function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In that case, the solution may be interpreted as an impulse that travels to the right or the left.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The basic wave equation is a linear differential equation, and so it will adhere to the superposition principle.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This means that the net displacement caused by two or more waves is the sum of the displacements which would have been caused by each wave individually.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In addition, the behavior of a wave can be analyzed by breaking up the wave into components, e.g. the Fourier transform breaks up a wave into sinusoidal components.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Another way to solve the one-dimensional wave equation is to first analyze its frequency eigenmodes.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Known as the Helmholtz equation, it has the well-known plane-wave solutions $f(x)=Ae^{\pm ikx},$ with wave number *k* = *ω*/*c*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The total wave function for this eigenmode is then the linear combination $u_{\omega }(x,t)=e^{-i\omega t}\left(Ae^{-ikx}+Be^{ikx}\right)=Ae^{-i(kx+\omega t)}+Be^{i(kx-\omega t)},$ where complex numbers A, B depend in general on any initial and boundary conditions of the problem.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Functions *s*±(*ω*) are known as the Fourier component and are determined by initial and boundary conditions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This is a so-called frequency-domain method, alternative to direct time-domain propagations, such as FDTD method, of the wave packet *u*(*x*, *t*), which is complete for representing waves in absence of time dilations.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Completeness of the Fourier expansion for representing waves in the presence of time dilations has been challenged by chirp wave solutions allowing for time variation of ω.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The vectorial wave equation (from which the scalar wave equation can be directly derived) can be obtained by applying a force equilibrium to an infinitesimal volume element.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] If the medium has a modulus of elasticity E that is homogeneous (i.e. independent of $\mathbf {x}$ ) within the volume element, then its stress tensor is given by $\mathbf {T} =E\nabla \mathbf {u}$ , for a vectorial elastic deflection $\mathbf {u} (\mathbf {x} ,t)$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] By merging density $\rho$ and elasticity module $E,$ the sound velocity $c={\sqrt {E/\rho }}$ results (material law).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The above vectorial partial differential equation of the 2nd order delivers two mutually independent solutions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] From the quadratic velocity term $c^{2}=(+c)^{2}=(-c)^{2}$ can be seen that there are two waves travelling in opposite directions $+c$ and $-c$ are possible, hence results the designation "two-way wave equation".
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] It can be shown for plane longitudinal wave propagation that the synthesis of two one-way wave equations leads to a general two-way wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] A solution of the initial-value problem for the wave equation in three space dimensions can be obtained from the corresponding solution for a spherical wave.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The result can then be also used to obtain the same solution in two space dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This is the Helmholtz equation and can be solved using separation of variables.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Then there is no angular dependence and the amplitude depends only on the radial distance, i.e., Ψ(**r**, *t*) → *u*(*r*, *t*).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This equation can be rewritten as ${\frac {\partial ^{2}(ru)}{\partial t^{2}}}-c^{2}{\frac {\partial ^{2}(ru)}{\partial r^{2}}}=0,$ where the quantity *ru* satisfies the one-dimensional wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Therefore, there are solutions in the form $u(r,t)={\frac {1}{r}}F(r-ct)+{\frac {1}{r}}G(r+ct),$ where F and G are general solutions to the one-dimensional wave equation and can be interpreted as respectively an outgoing and incoming spherical waves.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The outgoing wave can be generated by a point source, and they make possible sharp signals whose form is altered only by a decrease in amplitude as r increases (see an illustration of a spherical wave on the top right).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Such waves exist only in cases of space with odd dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] For physical examples of solutions to the 3D wave equation that possess angular dependence, see dipole radiation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Although the word "monochromatic" is not exactly accurate, since it refers to light or electromagnetic radiation with well-defined frequency, the spirit is to discover the eigenmode of the wave equation in three dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] From this we can observe that the peak intensity of the spherical-wave oscillation, characterized as the squared wave amplitude $I=|u(r,t)|^{2}={\frac {|A|^{2}}{r^{2}}},$ drops at the rate proportional to 1/*r*2, an example of the inverse-square law.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The wave equation is linear in u and is left unaltered by translations in space and time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Therefore, we can generate a great variety of solutions by translating and summing spherical waves.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Let *φ*(*ξ*, *η*, *ζ*) be an arbitrary function of three independent variables, and let the spherical wave form F be a delta function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Let a family of spherical waves have center at (*ξ*, *η*, *ζ*), and let r be the radial distance from that point.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] If u is a superposition of such waves with weighting function φ, then $u(t,x,y,z)={\frac {1}{4\pi c}}\iiint \varphi (\xi ,\eta ,\zeta ){\frac {\delta (r-ct)}{r}}\,d\xi \,d\eta \,d\zeta ;$ the denominator 4*πc* is a convenience.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] From the definition of the delta function, u may also be written as $u(t,x,y,z)={\frac {t}{4\pi }}\iint _{S}\varphi (x+ct\alpha ,y+ct\beta ,z+ct\gamma )\,d\omega ,$ where α, β, and γ are coordinates on the unit sphere S, and ω is the area element on S.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] These formulas provide the solution for the initial-value problem for the wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] They show that the solution at a given point P, given (*t*, *x*, *y*, *z*) depends only on the data on the sphere of radius *ct* that is intersected by the **light cone** drawn backwards from P.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] It does *not* depend upon data on the interior of this sphere.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Thus the interior of the sphere is a lacuna for the solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This phenomenon is called **Huygens' principle**.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] It is only true for odd numbers of space dimension, where for one dimension the integration is performed over the boundary of an interval with respect to the Dirac measure.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] We can use the three-dimensional theory to solve this problem if we regard u as a function in three dimensions that is independent of the third dimension.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] where α and β are the first two coordinates on the unit sphere, and d*ω* is the area element on the sphere.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] It is apparent that the solution at (*t*, *x*, *y*) depends not only on the data on the light cone where $(x-\xi )^{2}+(y-\eta )^{2}=c^{2}t^{2},$ but also on data that are interior to that cone.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Consider the inhomogeneous wave equation in $1+D$ dimensions $(\partial _{tt}-c^{2}\nabla ^{2})u=s(t,x)$ By rescaling time, we can set wave speed $c=1$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Since the wave equation $(\partial _{tt}-\nabla ^{2})u=s(t,x)$ has order 2 in time, there are two impulse responses: an acceleration impulse and a velocity impulse.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The effect of inflicting an acceleration impulse is to suddenly change the wave velocity $\partial _{t}u$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The effect of inflicting a velocity impulse is to suddenly change the wave displacement u .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] For acceleration impulse, $s(t,x)=\delta ^{D+1}(t,x)$ where $\delta$ is the Dirac delta function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The solution to this case is called the Green's function G for the wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] For velocity impulse, $s(t,x)=\partial _{t}\delta ^{D+1}(t,x)$ , so if we solve the Green function G , the solution for this case is just $\partial _{t}G$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The main use of Green's functions is to solve initial value problems by Duhamel's principle, both for the homogeneous and the inhomogeneous case.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Given the Green function G , and initial conditions $u(0,x),\partial _{t}u(0,x)$ , the solution to the homogeneous wave equation is $u=(\partial _{t}G)\ast u+G\ast \partial _{t}u$ where the asterisk is convolution in space.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] It would require us to perturb the integral slightly either by $+i\epsilon$ or by $-i\epsilon$ , because it is an improper integral.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] One perturbation gives the forward solution, and the other the backward solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] We can relate the Green's function in D dimensions to the Green's function in $D+n$ dimensions (lowering the dimension is possible in any case, raising is possible in spherical symmetry).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The Green's function in D dimensions can be related to the Green's function in $D+2$ dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The dimension can be raised to give the $D=3$ case $G_{3}(t,r)={\frac {\delta (t-r)}{4\pi r}}$ and similarly for the backward solution.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In $D=1$ case, the Green's function solution is the sum of two wavefronts ${\frac {\operatorname {sgn}(t-x)}{4}}+{\frac {\operatorname {sgn}(t+x)}{4}}$ moving in opposite directions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In odd dimensions, the forward solution is nonzero only at $t=r$ .
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] As the dimensions increase, the shape of wavefront becomes increasingly complex, involving higher derivatives of the Dirac delta function.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In even dimensions, the forward solution is nonzero in $r\leq t$ , the entire region behind the wavefront becomes nonzero, called a wake.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This means that a general Huygens' principle – the wave displacement at a point $(t,x)$ in spacetime depends only on the state at points on characteristic rays passing $(t,x)$ – only holds in odd dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] A physical interpretation is that signals transmitted by waves remain undistorted in odd dimensions, but distorted in even dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] For an incident wave traveling from one medium (where the wave speed is *c*1) to another medium (where the wave speed is *c*2), one part of the wave will transmit into the second medium, while another part reflects back into the other direction and stays in the first medium.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The amplitude of the transmitted wave and the reflected wave can be calculated by using the continuity condition at the boundary.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Consider the component of the incident wave with an angular frequency of ω, which has the waveform $u^{\text{inc}}(x,t)=Ae^{i(k_{1}x-\omega t)},\quad A\in \mathbb {C} .$ At *t* = 0, the incident reaches the boundary between the two media at *x* = 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The energy conservation can be verified by ${\frac {B^{2}}{c_{1}}}+{\frac {C^{2}}{c_{2}}}={\frac {A^{2}}{c_{1}}}.$ The above discussion holds true for any component, regardless of its angular frequency of ω.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The limiting case of *c*2 = 0 corresponds to a "fixed end" that does not move, whereas the limiting case of *c*2 → ∞ corresponds to a "free end".
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] A flexible string that is stretched between two points *x* = 0 and *x* = *L* satisfies the wave equation for *t* > 0 and 0 < *x* < *L*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] On the boundary points, u may satisfy a variety of boundary conditions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The case where u is required to vanish at an endpoint (i.e.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] "fixed end") is the limit of this condition when the respective a or b approaches infinity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This is a special case of the general problem of Sturm–Liouville theory.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] If a and b are positive, the eigenvalues are all positive, and the solutions are trigonometric functions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] A solution that satisfies square-integrable initial conditions for u and *ut* can be obtained from expansion of these functions in the appropriate trigonometric series.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The one-dimensional initial-boundary value theory may be extended to an arbitrary number of space dimensions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Consider a domain D in m-dimensional x space, with boundary B.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Then the wave equation is to be satisfied if x is in D, and *t* > 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] where n is the unit outward normal to B, and a is a non-negative function defined on B.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The case where u vanishes on B is a limiting case for a approaching infinity.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This problem may be solved by expanding f and g in the eigenfunctions of the Laplacian in D, which satisfy the boundary conditions.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In the case of two space dimensions, the eigenfunctions may be interpreted as the modes of vibration of a drumhead stretched over the boundary B.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] If B is a circle, then these eigenfunctions have an angular component that is a trigonometric function of the polar angle θ, multiplied by a Bessel function (of integer order) of the radial component.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Further details are in Helmholtz equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] If the boundary is a sphere in three space dimensions, the angular components of the eigenfunctions are spherical harmonics, and the radial components are Bessel functions of half-integer order.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The function *s*(*x*, *t*) is often called the source function because in practice it describes the effects of the sources of waves on the medium carrying them.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Physical examples of source functions include the force driving a wave on a string, or the charge or current density in the Lorenz gauge of electromagnetism.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] One method to solve the initial-value problem (with the initial values as posed above) is to take advantage of a special property of the wave equation in an odd number of space dimensions, namely that its solutions respect causality.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] That is, for any point (*xi*, *ti*), the value of *u*(*xi*, *ti*) depends only on the values of *f*(*xi* + *cti*) and *f*(*xi* − *cti*) and the values of the function *g*(*x*) between (*xi* − *cti*) and (*xi* + *cti*).
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] This can be seen in d'Alembert's formula, stated above, where these quantities are the only ones that show up in it.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Physically, if the maximum propagation speed is c, then no part of the wave that cannot propagate to a given point by a given time can affect the amplitude at the same point and time.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In terms of finding a solution, this causality property means that for any given point on the line being considered, the only area that needs to be considered is the area encompassing all the points that could causally affect the point being considered.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Denote the area that causally affects point (*xi*, *ti*) as *RC*.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The left side is now the sum of three line integrals along the bounds of the causality region.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In the above, the term to be integrated with respect to time disappears because the time interval involved is zero, thus *dt* = 0.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] For the other two sides of the region, it is worth noting that *x* ± *ct* is a constant, namely *xi* ± *cti*, where the sign is chosen appropriately.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] In the last equation of the sequence, the bounds of the integral over the source function have been made explicit.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Looking at this solution, which is valid for all choices (*xi*, *ti*) compatible with the wave equation, it is clear that the first two terms are simply d'Alembert's formula, as stated above as the solution of the homogeneous wave equation in one dimension.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The difference is in the third term, the integral over the source.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] The elastic wave equation (also known as the Navier–Cauchy equation) in three dimensions describes the propagation of waves in an isotropic homogeneous elastic medium.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Most solid materials are elastic, so this equation describes such phenomena as seismic waves in the Earth and ultrasonic waves used to detect flaws in materials.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] By using ∇ × (∇ × **u**) = ∇(∇ ⋅ **u**) − ∇ ⋅ ∇ **u** = ∇(∇ ⋅ **u**) − ∆**u**, the elastic wave equation can be rewritten into the more common form of the Navier–Cauchy equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Note that in the elastic wave equation, both force and displacement are vector quantities.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] Thus, this equation is sometimes known as the vector wave equation.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] As an aid to understanding, the reader will observe that if **f** and ∇ ⋅ **u** are set to zero, this becomes (effectively) Maxwell's equation for the propagation of the electric field **E**, which has only transverse waves.
[src:partial-differential-equations/wave-equation] where ω is the angular frequency, and **k** is the wavevector describing plane-wave solutions.
